---
name: devops-report
description: Generate a sprint status report in markdown showing completion %, outstanding items, and recommendations. Use for stand-ups, sprint reviews, or when asked "how are we tracking" / "what's left".
---

Generate a sprint status report for the Charter Hall MSM project.

## Azure DevOps Config

- Org: `https://dev.azure.com/acclt-daas`
- Project: `Charter Hall - MSM Implementation`
- Iteration path pattern: `Charter Hall - MSM Implementation\Phase 1\Sprint N`

## Encoding Note

Always use PowerShell (not bash) to run `az` commands — it handles encoding correctly. Pattern:

```
powershell.exe -Command "az boards ... | Out-File -Encoding utf8 C:\Users\dinne\AppData\Local\Temp\sprint_data.json"
```

Then read the file with Python using `encoding='utf-8', errors='replace'` and strip any BOM (`lstrip('\ufeff')`), then skip any leading WARNING lines before the JSON starts.

## Step 1: Identify Current Sprint

```
powershell.exe -Command "az boards iteration team list --team 'Charter Hall - MSM Implementation Team' --org https://dev.azure.com/acclt-daas --project 'Charter Hall - MSM Implementation'"
```

Find the entry with `"timeFrame": "current"` — that's the sprint name and date range to use.

## Step 2: Query All Sprint Items

Replace `Sprint N` with the current sprint name:

```
powershell.exe -Command "az boards query --wiql \"SELECT [System.Id], [System.Title], [System.State], [System.WorkItemType], [System.AssignedTo] FROM WorkItems WHERE [System.TeamProject] = 'Charter Hall - MSM Implementation' AND [System.IterationPath] UNDER 'Charter Hall - MSM Implementation\Phase 1\Sprint N' AND [System.State] <> 'Removed' ORDER BY [System.State], [System.Id]\" --org https://dev.azure.com/acclt-daas --project 'Charter Hall - MSM Implementation' | Out-File -Encoding utf8 C:\Users\dinne\AppData\Local\Temp\sprint_report.json"
```

Parse the JSON with Python to extract: id, title, state, type, assigned_to (displayName).

Done states: `Closed`, `Resolved`, `Done`.

## Step 3: Cross-reference with Repo

Scan the working directory for work that relates to open tickets:
- Python scripts that implement functionality described in open tickets
- SQL views that correspond to activity type stories
- Task folders (`<name>-<id>/`) with completed steps in `task.md`
- Recent git commits mentioning ticket IDs

## Step 4: Generate Report

Output the report in this format:

```markdown
# Sprint N Status Report

**Date**: {today}
**Sprint**: {start_date} to {end_date}
**Overall**: {done}/{total} ({pct}%)

## Completion by Person

| Person | Done | Total | % |
|--------|------|-------|---|
| {name} | {done} | {total} | {pct}% |

## State Breakdown

| State | Count |
|-------|-------|
| Closed | N |
| Active | N |
| New | N |

## Outstanding Items

### {Person} ({count} open)

| ID | Type | State | Title |
|----|------|-------|-------|
| {id} | {type} | {state} | {title} |

## Recommended Closures

Items that appear done based on work in the repo:

| ID | Title | Reason |
|----|-------|--------|
| {id} | {title} | {why} |

## Notes

- {observations about sprint health, blockers, risks}
```

Display the key numbers in chat and offer to save the full report to `tmp/sprint-report-{date}.md`.
